docs.lead_paragraph: Today’s newsletter is a dispatch from our colleagues in the tech bureau who have been covering the spread of disinformation in the aftermath of the election. First this from Davey Alba:

headline.main: What You Need to Know About the Election and Disinformation

byline.original: By Davey Alba and Joseph Plambeck

docs.abstract: His latest fit reminds me of a toddler’s. Except 3-year-olds don’t hold the power of the presidency.
docs.snippet: His latest fit reminds me of a toddler’s. Except 3-year-olds don’t hold the power of the presidency.
docs.lead_paragraph: When my oldest son was 3 years old we got him into a preschool class at an elite private school across the street from Prospect Park in the Park Slope neighborhood of Brooklyn.

headline.main: Trump’s Election Tantrum

docs.abstract: “Voters, not lawyers, choose the president,” a judge for the Third Circuit Court of Appeals wrote in the 21-page repudiation of Mr. Trump’s legal effort to halt Pennsylvania’s certification process.
docs.snippet: “Voters, not lawyers, choose the president,” a judge for the Third Circuit Court of Appeals wrote in the 21-page repudiation of Mr. Trump’s legal effort to halt Pennsylvania’s certification process.
docs.lead_paragraph: In a blistering decision, a Philadelphia appeals court ruled on Friday that the Trump campaign could not stop — or attempt to reverse — the certification of the voting results in Pennsylvania, reprimanding the president’s team by noting that “calling an election unfair does not make it so.”

headline.main: In Harsh Rebuke, Appeals Court Rejects Trump’s Election Challenge in Pennsylvania
headline.print_headline: Scathing Ruling Sinks President In Pennsylvania

docs.abstract: Mr. Krebs had overseen election cybersecurity efforts, and had joined other officials in declaring the 2020 election “the most secure in American history.”
docs.snippet: Mr. Krebs had overseen election cybersecurity efforts, and had joined other officials in declaring the 2020 election “the most secure in American history.”
docs.lead_paragraph: President Trump on Tuesday night fired his administration’s most senior cybersecurity official responsible for securing the presidential election, Christopher Krebs, who had systematically disputed Mr. Trump’s false declarations in recent days that the presidency was stolen from him through fraudulent ballots and software glitches that changed millions of votes.

headline.main: Trump Fires Christopher Krebs, Official Who Disputed Election Fraud Claims
headline.print_headline: Trump Fires Top Cybersecurity Official Who Refuted Claims of Election Fraud

byline.original: By David E. Sanger and Nicole Perlroth

docs.abstract: Yet Philadelphia, Milwaukee and Detroit have become the targets of G.O.P. allegations of voting shenanigans.
docs.snippet: Yet Philadelphia, Milwaukee and Detroit have become the targets of G.O.P. allegations of voting shenanigans.
docs.lead_paragraph: In Pennsylvania, much of President Trump’s attention since the election has focused on Philadelphia, where he has baselessly insisted there is a “mountain of corruption.” In Michigan, litigation by Mr. Trump’s campaign has concentrated on Detroit, where Republican poll watchers say they felt intimidated by election workers in Black Lives Matter apparel. And in Wisconsin, legal challenges and rumors have circled around Milwaukee, where one internet conspiracy  theory turns on a briefly misplaced flash drive of election results.

headline.main: The Cities Central to Fraud Conspiracy Theories Didn’t Cost Trump the Election
headline.print_headline: Conspiracy Theories Center on Cities That Didn’t Cost Trump the Election
